Purpose: Create Python companion file for recipe 12.1 Appointment Volume Forecasting

[49m[38;5;10m+       1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 12.1: Python Implementation Example
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Heads up:** This is a deliberately simple, illustrative implementation of the pseudocode walkthrough from Recipe 12.1. It shows one way you could translate appointment volume forecasting into working Python using boto3 against Amazon S3, Amazon Athena, Amazon SageMaker (for hosted training as an option), Amazon EventBridge Scheduler, and Amazon CloudWatch, with [Prophet](https://facebook.github.io/prophet/) doing the actual time series fitting. It is not production-ready. There is no real Athena workgroup configured, no real SageMaker Processing job, no daily backtest dashboard, no holiday calendar curated for your specific region, no per-clinic model registry, no drift detection, no on-call alerting, no per-cohort fairness checks. Think of it as the sketchpad version: useful for understanding the shape of an operational forecasting pipeline that respects the data-prep discipline, the model-fit discipline, the forecast-validation discipline, the hand-off-to-staffing discipline, and the audit-everything discipline this recipe needs. It is not something you would point at next week's staffing schedule on Monday morning. Consider it a starting point, not a destination.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m >
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > The pipeline follows seven steps. Pull historical appointment counts out of the warehouse (Step 1). Aggregate them into a clean daily time series with calendar features (Step 2). Fit a forecasting model that handles weekly seasonality, annual seasonality, and named holidays (Step 3). Generate a forecast with prediction intervals over the planning horizon (Step 4). Write the forecast to S3 in a stable format that staffing tools can consume (Step 5). Publish operational metrics so you know when forecasts drift (Step 6). Run a rolling backtest on last week's forecast against last week's actuals so you have a current accuracy number, not a stale one (Step 7). Each step maps 1:1 to the pseudocode in the main recipe.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m >
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > The synthetic appointment counts in the demo are fictional. Nothing here is clinical advice or operational advice for any real institution. Volume forecasts are operational decisions; they inform staffing, not patient care.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Setup
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m You will need the AWS SDK for Python plus a couple of forecasting libraries:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```bash
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m pip install boto3 pandas prophet
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Prophet pulls in `cmdstanpy` and a compiled Stan model on first import, so the first import is slow (a minute or two) and needs a working C++ toolchain. In a Lambda or container deployment, build the wheel into the image rather than installing at runtime.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Your environment needs credentials configured (via environment variables, an instance profile, or `~/.aws/credentials`). The IAM role or user needs:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `athena:StartQueryExecution`, `athena:GetQueryExecution`, `athena:GetQueryResults`, and `athena:StopQueryExecution` on the workgroup that holds your appointment data
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `glue:GetTable`, `glue:GetDatabase`, and `glue:GetPartitions` on the data catalog that backs the appointment table
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `s3:GetObject` and `s3:ListBucket` on the bucket holding the historical appointment data Athena reads from
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `s3:GetObject` and `s3:PutObject` on the Athena query-results bucket prefix
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `s3:PutObject` and `s3:GetObject` on the forecast-output bucket prefix
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `cloudwatch:PutMetricData` for the operational metrics (forecast staleness, MAPE, holiday-aware-MAPE, per-clinic forecast bias, latest-forecast-horizon)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `kms:Decrypt` and `kms:GenerateDataKey` on the customer-managed keys protecting the warehouse data, the Athena results, and the forecast-output bucket
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `sagemaker:CreateProcessingJob`, `sagemaker:DescribeProcessingJob`, and `iam:PassRole` if you run the training as a SageMaker Processing job rather than inline (the alternative shown at the end of the file)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Scope each role to the specific resource ARNs it touches. The tutorial-level permissions above are fine for learning and will fail any serious IAM review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things worth knowing upfront:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Appointment counts are PHI-adjacent.** A daily count of cardiology appointments at a specific clinic is not PHI in the strict HIPAA sense. The underlying records are. Run the aggregation inside the trusted analytics environment (Athena workgroup, SageMaker Processing job in a private VPC), only the aggregates leave that boundary, and the aggregates still carry access controls because they reveal operational patterns (clinic capacity, demand shifts) that competitors and bad actors find useful. Aggregation is a privacy primitive, not a free pass.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Forecasts are operational. Mistakes are operational.** Under-forecasting demand leaves the clinic short-staffed and the patient experience suffers. Over-forecasting wastes labor. Neither is clinical. The models below are tuned for operational utility, not clinical-grade calibration. The clinical-grade calibration story is in chapter 12.7, 12.9, and 12.10 where the forecasts directly inform clinical action.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Holidays matter more than the model.** A Prophet model with a clean holiday calendar consistently beats a fancier model with the default U.S. federal-holidays list. The clinic's holiday is the day the clinic is closed or the day after Thanksgiving when half the staff is on PTO, not the literal calendar holiday. Curate the holiday calendar; the rest is mechanics.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Outliers belong in the data, not in the model.** Snowstorm closures, system outages, COVID-era discontinuities, and one-off mass-cancellation events distort the seasonal estimates Prophet learns. Mark them as known anomalies in the input data (one row per anomalous date with a flag) and either exclude them from the fit or model them as one-off regressors. Letting them flow through unmodeled bakes them into the seasonal pattern and the next year's forecasts inherit the distortion.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Forecasts are stale the moment they are generated.** A weekly forecast generated Monday morning is fine for the staffing meeting Tuesday afternoon. By the time Friday's actual count rolls in, the forecast has new evidence to absorb. The pipeline runs daily, not just weekly, so the forecast is never more than a day old. The CloudWatch alarm on forecast staleness is the safety net.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The downstream consumer is the staffing tool, not a dashboard.** The forecast lives in S3 in a stable schema (date, clinic, channel, mean, lower_80, upper_80, lower_95, upper_95) that the staffing tool reads. The dashboard is a side-effect for humans to spot-check; the operational consumer is a service. Treat the schema as a contract with a documented version history.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **DynamoDB is not used in this recipe.** Forecasts are append-only, time-keyed, batch-produced data. S3 with partitioning by forecast_run_date is the right primitive. DynamoDB would be over-engineered.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Pandas in Lambda is heavy.** Pandas plus Prophet plus pyarrow plus their dependencies easily exceed Lambda's 250 MB unzipped layer cap. The example below assumes a Lambda container image (10 GB cap) or a SageMaker Processing job. The plain-Lambda-with-layers path is a tighter squeeze and usually not worth the tradeoffs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Configuration and Constants
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Everything that is configuration rather than logic lives here. Resource names, the warehouse query, the forecast horizon, the holiday list, and the alerting thresholds are what you would change between environments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import io
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import logging
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import time
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import uuid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from typing import Optional
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import boto3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import pandas as pd
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from botocore.config import Config
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Structured logging. In production, ship JSON-formatted records to
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # CloudWatch Logs Insights so you can join across the daily-fit run,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # the staffing tool's forecast-consumption events, and the actuals
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # that come back through the pipeline tomorrow. Forecast inputs and
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # outputs are aggregates; logging the aggregate counts is fine.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # The underlying patient-level records are not in scope for this
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # pipeline at all. Aggregation happens in Athena, not in this code.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m logger.setLevel(logging.INFO)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Adaptive retry handles throttling from Athena (workgroups have
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # concurrent-query limits), CloudWatch (PutMetricData is rate-limited
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # per account per region), and S3 during the daily refresh window
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # when the rest of the analytics platform is also running.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG = Config(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     retries={"max_attempts": 5, "mode": "adaptive"})
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Module-level clients. Reused across Lambda invocations in warm
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # containers so each invocation does not pay the connection cost.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m REGION = "us-east-1"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m athena_client     = boto3.client("athena",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                   region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                   config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m s3_client         = boto3.client("s3",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                   region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                   config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m cloudwatch_client = boto3.client("cloudwatch",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                   region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                   config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m sagemaker_client  = boto3.client("sagemaker",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                   region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                   config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Resource Names ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Fill these in with your actual resource names.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ATHENA_WORKGROUP            = "analytics-prod"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ATHENA_DATABASE             = "operations_warehouse"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ATHENA_OUTPUT_S3_URI        = (
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "s3://analytics-athena-results-prod/forecasting/")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m APPOINTMENT_FACT_TABLE      = "appt_fact"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m HISTORICAL_APPT_S3_BUCKET   = "operations-warehouse-prod"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FORECAST_OUTPUT_BUCKET      = "operations-forecasts-prod"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FORECAST_OUTPUT_PREFIX      = "appointment-volume/"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ANOMALY_OVERRIDES_KEY       = (
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "appointment-volume/config/anomaly-overrides.csv")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m HOLIDAYS_OVERRIDES_KEY      = (
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "appointment-volume/config/holidays.csv")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m CLOUDWATCH_NAMESPACE        = "AppointmentVolumeForecasting"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Deploy-time guardrail. Any blank resource name is a deploy-time
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # bug, not a runtime surprise.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m for _name, _value in [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("ATHENA_WORKGROUP",          ATHENA_WORKGROUP),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("ATHENA_DATABASE",           ATHENA_DATABASE),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("ATHENA_OUTPUT_S3_URI",      ATHENA_OUTPUT_S3_URI),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("APPOINTMENT_FACT_TABLE",    APPOINTMENT_FACT_TABLE),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("HISTORICAL_APPT_S3_BUCKET", HISTORICAL_APPT_S3_BUCKET),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("FORECAST_OUTPUT_BUCKET",    FORECAST_OUTPUT_BUCKET),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("FORECAST_OUTPUT_PREFIX",    FORECAST_OUTPUT_PREFIX),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("CLOUDWATCH_NAMESPACE",      CLOUDWATCH_NAMESPACE),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     assert _value, f"{_name} must be set before deploying."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Forecasting Knobs ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # How far back to pull history. Three full years of history gives
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Prophet enough data to learn yearly seasonality with confidence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # and to absorb one-off shocks without distorting the seasonal fit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m HISTORY_LOOKBACK_DAYS       = 365 * 3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # How far ahead to forecast. Eight weeks covers staffing planning
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # horizons (most clinics plan four weeks; supervisors look two
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # months ahead). Beyond this the prediction intervals widen so much
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # the forecast is decorative.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FORECAST_HORIZON_DAYS       = 56
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Cohort axes. Forecast is generated per (clinic, channel) pair so
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # the staffing tool can consume forecasts at the same grain at
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # which it makes decisions. A facility with three clinics and
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # in-person/telehealth channels produces six forecasts per run.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m COHORT_AXES                 = ["clinic_code", "channel"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Minimum history required before we trust a per-cohort fit. With
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # fewer than this many distinct dates the model is fitting noise.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Below the threshold, fall back to the parent clinic's pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # scaled by the cohort's average ratio.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m MIN_HISTORY_DAYS_PER_COHORT = 365
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Backtest cadence. Every daily run scores last week's forecast
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # (T-7 to T-1 generated last Monday) against last week's actuals
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # and emits MAPE and bias to CloudWatch. The on-call alarm fires
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # on a 7-day rolling MAPE above the threshold.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m BACKTEST_DAYS               = 7
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m BACKTEST_MAPE_ALARM         = 0.20  # 20% MAPE triggers review
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Forecast schema versioning ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # The downstream staffing tool reads the schema by version. Bump
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # the version in lockstep with any field addition or removal.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FORECAST_SCHEMA_VERSION     = "1.2"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Athena query ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Pull (date, clinic, channel, count) for the lookback window. The
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # warehouse table is one row per appointment. We aggregate in
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Athena so only the daily counts leave the trusted analytics
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # environment. The patient-level rows never enter this Python file.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m APPT_AGGREGATION_SQL = """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     SELECT
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         date(appointment_date) AS appt_date,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         clinic_code,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         channel,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         COUNT(*) AS appt_count
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FROM {database}.{table}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     WHERE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         appointment_date BETWEEN DATE '{start_date}'
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                               AND DATE '{end_date}'
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         AND status IN ('booked', 'completed', 'arrived',
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                        'in-progress', 'fulfilled')
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     GROUP BY 1, 2, 3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ORDER BY 1, 2, 3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m """.strip()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Shared Helpers
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few small utilities used across steps. Keeping them together so each step's code stays focused on the pattern it teaches.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def _now_iso() -> str:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """Current UTC time in ISO-8601 format."""
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def _today_utc_date() -> datetime:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """Today's UTC date with time stripped."""
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return datetime.now(timezone.utc).replace(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         hour=0, minute=0, second=0, microsecond=0)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def _put_metric(metric_name: str,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                  value: float,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                  dimensions: dict,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                  unit: str = "None") -> None:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """Emit a CloudWatch metric. Best-effort; never blocks the run."""
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     try:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         cloudwatch_client.put_metric_data(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             Namespace=CLOUDWATCH_NAMESPACE,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             MetricData=[{
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 "MetricName": metric_name,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 "Value":      float(value),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 "Unit":       unit,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 "Dimensions": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     {"Name": k, "Value": str(v)}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     for k, v in dimensions.items()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     except Exception as exc:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         logger.error(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "CloudWatch put_metric_data failed for %s: %s",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             metric_name, exc)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Step 1: Pull Historical Appointment Counts from the Warehouse
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m *The pseudocode calls this `pull_history(lookback_days)`. The forecasting pipeline needs daily appointment counts per cohort over the lookback window. The warehouse holds one row per appointment, so we aggregate in Athena rather than pulling raw rows. The aggregates are what enter this Python file; the row-level data never does.*
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def pull_history(lookback_days: int = HISTORY_LOOKBACK_DAYS
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                   ) -> pd.DataFrame:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Run the aggregation query in Athena and return a tidy DataFrame.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         DataFrame with columns: appt_date (datetime64),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         clinic_code (str), channel (str), appt_count (int).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end_date = _today_utc_date().date()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     start_date = end_date - timedelta(days=lookback_days)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     query = APPT_AGGREGATION_SQL.format(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         database=ATHENA_DATABASE,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         table=APPOINTMENT_FACT_TABLE,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         start_date=start_date.isoformat(),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         end_date=end_date.isoformat())
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Start the query. Athena runs asynchronously; we poll for
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # completion. ClientRequestToken makes the start idempotent
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # so a retried Step Functions step does not start duplicate
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # queries.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     request_token = (
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         f"appt-volume-fcst-{end_date.isoformat()}-"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         f"{uuid.uuid4().hex[:8]}")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     response = athena_client.start_query_execution(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         QueryString=query,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         QueryExecutionContext={"Database": ATHENA_DATABASE},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         WorkGroup=ATHENA_WORKGROUP,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ResultConfiguration={
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "OutputLocation": ATHENA_OUTPUT_S3_URI,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ClientRequestToken=request_token)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     query_id = response["QueryExecutionId"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("Started Athena query %s", query_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Poll for completion. Tune the polling interval to your
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # workgroup's typical query latency. Athena charges per byte
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # scanned; the workgroup's data-usage controls protect against
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # a runaway query bankrupting the budget. Configure those.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     deadline = time.time() + 600  # 10 minute hard cap
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state = "QUEUED"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     while time.time() < deadline:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         execution = athena_client.get_query_execution(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             QueryExecutionId=query_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         state = execution["QueryExecution"]["Status"]["State"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         if state in ("SUCCEEDED", "FAILED", "CANCELLED"):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             break
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         time.sleep(2)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     if state != "SUCCEEDED":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reason = (execution["QueryExecution"]["Status"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                   .get("StateChangeReason", "unknown"))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         raise RuntimeError(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             f"Athena query {query_id} ended in {state}: {reason}")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Pull the result set. For larger result sets, page through
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # `get_query_results` with NextToken. For very large sets
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # (>1M rows), read the result CSV directly from
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # S3 instead.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     rows = []
